🎯 2. Add Severity Levels (This makes it feel REAL)
def get_severity(size):
    if size > 1500:
        return "HIGH"
    elif size > 800:
        return "MEDIUM"
    return "LOW"

Now alerts become:

{
  "type": "DDoS Attack",
  "severity": "HIGH",
  "message": "Large packet flood detected"
}
📊 3. Add a “Threat Score” (This is impressive in demos)

Give each request a score out of 100:

df["threat_score"] = (
    (df["size"] / df["size"].max()) * 50 +
    (df["anomaly"] == -1).astype(int) * 50
)

Now you can say:

“This traffic has a 92% threat probability”

That sounds powerful.

🧠 4. Add Memory (Trend Detection)

Right now your model forgets everything every run.

Add this:

if df["anomaly"].tail(5).sum() < 0:
    alerts.append({
        "type": "pattern",
        "message": "Repeated anomalies detected (Possible ongoing attack)"
    })

Now your system detects ongoing attacks, not just single events.

🌐 5. Add IP + Geo Simulation (Game Changer for Demo)

Modify DB:

ALTER TABLE traffic ADD COLUMN ip TEXT;

Then fake IPs:

import random

fake_ip = f"192.168.{random.randint(0,255)}.{random.randint(0,255)}"

Now your alerts look like:

{
  "ip": "192.168.23.91",
  "attack": "DDoS",
  "severity": "HIGH"
}

Feels like a real cybersecurity tool instantly.

